Oh well - ma was very - she was - a woman that - liked to be - things to be done in a proper way you know. And - and that was a - she - we - being left with two of
 us, she knew - she knew how to handle us. She got to know how to handle us, until I was up until - well I was - until I went into the Army, until I went to the Army she was - she looked after me. Aye. And then I was in Canada. I was in Canada when I come
 
home from Canada, I used to worry about her when I was away in Canada in Montreal, and I worked for the Standard Charcoal Company in Ontario, and when I came home and I knocked at the door - and I knocked at the door and my mother saw me - sometimes - I f
e
el the tears coming down my eyes when I think about it. She said, oh my son. I thought I'd never see you again. I says, mother, many a time I thought the same about you. I says, and that's the reason why - I left Canada behind, with all its attractions an
d - all the big things you know. I says, well I - I'll join the Army. I joined the Army and - I served my time in the Army and -
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid9049349 I  : }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0 \ltrch\fcs0 \lang2057\langfe1033\langnp2057\insrsid13703802\charrsid1209268 Did your mother used to go to church on a Sunday?
